<p><a name="Types_of_chords" id="Types_of_chords"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Chord_(music)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Types of chords">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Types of chords</span></h2>
<p><a name="Tertian_triads" id="Tertian_triads"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Chord_(music)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Tertian triads">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Tertian triads</span></h3>
<p>Tertian triads can be described as a series of three notes. The first element is called the <a href="/wiki/Root_note" title="Root note" class="mw-redirect">root note</a> of the chord, the second note is called the "third" of the chord, and the last note is called the "fifth" of the chord. These are described below:</p>
<table class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;">
<tr>
<th>Chord name</th>
<th colspan="2">Component intervals</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th><a href="/wiki/Chord_(music)#Pop_chord_notation" title="Chord (music)">Chord symbol</a></th>
<th>Audio</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th><a href="/wiki/Major_chord" title="Major chord">major triad</a></th>
<td><a href="/wiki/Major_third" title="Major third">major third</a></td>
<td><a href="/wiki/Perfect_fifth" title="Perfect fifth">perfect fifth</a></td>
<td>C-E-G</td>
<td>C, CM, Cma, Cmaj, CΔ</td>
